1ï¸âƒ£ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
ğŸ”¹ What is the Vedic Age?

The Vedic Age (c. 1500â€“600 BCE) refers to the period when the Vedas were composed.
It is divided into:

Early Vedic Period (Rig Vedic)

Later Vedic Period

UPSC focuses on society, polity, economy, religion, and changes over time.

ğŸ”¹ Early Vedic Period (Rig Vedic Age)

Society

Tribal society, semi-nomadic

Family was patriarchal

No rigid caste system

Women had relatively better status

Polity

Tribe (Jana) was the political unit

King (Rajan) was not absolute

Popular assemblies: Sabha & Samiti

Economy

Pastoral economy

Cow was measure of wealth

Limited agriculture

Religion

Nature worship

Important gods: Indra, Agni, Varuna

No temples or idols

ğŸ”¹ Later Vedic Period

Society

Varna system became rigid (Brahmin, Kshatriya, Vaishya, Shudra)

Decline in womenâ€™s status

Rise of social inequalities

Polity

Kings became powerful

Large kingdoms replaced tribes

Assemblies lost importance

Economy

Agriculture dominant

Iron tools (later phase)

Surplus production

Religion

Rituals and sacrifices increased

Priests (Brahmins) became dominant

Emergence of Upanishadic philosophy

ğŸ“Œ UPSC Focus:
Comparisons between Early vs Later Vedic, not memorising hymns.

